{"/service/ndnp/okhi/batch_okhi_falafel_ver01/data/sn86090528/00295864485/1908012301/1020.xml":{"full_text":"TH\nTT TT-.T KHH'K\nII. EVANS, r.j;tor. ERYCn P. SMITH, Business Manager\nTELEPHONE ISTUMBER, 4-3.\nEntered at the Fostofiice ia the City of Chickasha, Oklahoma, as Mat\nter of the Second Class.\nCHICKASHA, OKLA., JANUARY 23. 1908\nerf.1..\nWHO WILL BUY?\nI J. Hauler of Washington, la., has prepared end sent to the\nCommoner the following interesting matter which he suggests that\nrepublican politicians might use as a hand bill:\nrL'P.LIC SALE\nOur lease with Uncle Sam having practically expired, and hav\ning decided to quit the business, and retire to private life, we the\nundersigned, will offer at public sale at our residence, at the\nCapitol in Washington, D. C, commencing on the second day of\nDecember, 1907, the following described property, towit:\nOne elephant about forty-five years old.\nOne financial panic old enough to be leaned.\nOne republican platform, the game being somewhat rotten.\nOne big stick.\nOne republican machine, the same being somewhat out of re\npair. One financial system.\nFifty millions Teddy Bears; and other articles too numerous\nto mention,\nTerms of sale, cash.\nQ. 0. P., Owners,\nRockcfellr Morgan, Clorks.Wnll Street, Auctioneer.\nWhile it is believed that most of the above mentioned articles\nwill he purchased as relics, by the standpatters, still we have been\ninformed on good authority that it is the earnest desire of the\nG. 0. P. that the democratic party be present at the sale and\nthus show their interest and good will in the same, even though\nthey don't, sec anything they care to purchase The Commoner.\ni\nJ J fuJt\nDuring the campaign last summer a republican argument\nagainst the constitution was that it would keep capital out of the\nstate, and that a democratic legislature would be still more un\nfriendly to capital. Leo Harris of Carter county, has introduced\na bill which refutes these statements, puts an unusual premium on\nenterprises requiring large capital, and will do much toward in\nducing the location of new mills and factories in the state. 1 lis bill\nprovides that any incorporated town or city may, by a vote of the\npeople, exempt from municipal taxation any manufacturing estab\nlishment or public utility, for a term not exceeding five years.\nGuthrie Leader.\nREAL ESTATE SELLS WELL\n-COL HUBBARD MADE GOOD\n-NEWSPAPER STARTED\nThe Amber lot sale yesterday prov\ned to be a great success. In about\n2 Lours 75 lots sold ranging in price\nfrom ?20 to $100 for residences, and\nbusiness property from $ti.\" to $225.\nTwo corner lots brought the latter\nfigure.\nThe crowd was not large but they\nhad money and meant business. Many\npaid cash and took the discount.\nA significant feature of the day was\nthe publication of tne first issue of\nThe Amber Record and Register\na newsy little paper edited by P. C.\nCOL. E. J. HUBBARD\nThe Auctioneer\nTo start the new state to housekeeping necessarily requires a\ny&t sum of money. Republicans will raise the cry of extrava\ngance in the next eainuaign no matter how strict economy i pract iced\nin making appropriations, but the legislature should see to it that\nthere are no grounds for making the charge. If there are any\nsupernumeraries sitting around the legislature or in any of the\ndepartments drawing fat salariees for little work, 1Q 'em off.\nCreate no more offices and incur no more expense of auy kind\nthan is necessary for the efficient administration of government.\nThe committee on retrencmcnt should keep busy.\noj0\nOklahoma stepped right into the lime light when she passed\nthe depositors' guarantee law and she again shows her progressive\nness by taking the lead in an aggressive campaign for the direct\nelection of United States senators. All during the late campaign,\nthe republicans howled that the state would be buried in the depths\nnf UmirhmiiRm would dron into the column of slow ones. if\nVfc i\nthe democrats won. The administration has already given the peo\npie ample evidence that such j lens were pure buncombe.\n0j!0\nThe spontaneous outburst \"of paving etitluiKiasm is gratifying\nin the extreme. Now, can't somebody start a sidewalk and cross\ning spasm? We need the paving, but the latter improvements are\neven more urgently needed and they don't cost half as much. The\nExpress wouldn't be guilty of dipeourgaing anyone piously inelin-\nfd toward paving, but it insists that there's a whole lot of gooc\nreligion, common sense and decency in havng sidewalks.\nEst.es. The lot buyers were strongly\nimpressed with the advantage of Am\nber and the excellent prospects .for a\ngood town.\nCol. 15. J. Hubbard conducted th\nsale and the success of it demon\nstrted his ability in this line. Messrs.\nFrey Hollingsworth, the promoters\nof the town were highly pleased with\nCol. Hubbard's work and the results\nof the sale. The colonel knows how\nto talk real estate In a business way,\nand that is the secret of his success.\n'RICE i HIS\n1 lz EE f\nEvery Picture in our\nstock is on sale at half\nthe regular price for this\nweek only.\nTHF flWI RRIiii STORF\nM PHONE 12S\nThe Express believes that the council should pass an ordinance\nlevying occupation tax of at least $500 a year on knockers. If it\nis objected that the price is apt to pro v prohibitive, it is sufficient\nto reply that that is the object of it.\nojjo\nIt must be a matter of general regret that Tom Lawsou has\nsounded a retreat in bis war on \"the system\" before springing th\n\"remedy.\"\nFOR SALE\n437. Your, opportunity. One-half\nblock in south part of town, vacant,\nwell located, to sell on easy terms\nfor $1,100.\n439. Vacant lots, f0 x 165 feet In\nsouthwest part of the city, well located\nnear business district, purchaser may\nbuild his home and pay for lota at\npleasure. See us at once.\nEighty acres good prairie land with\nin one mile of Alex, Okla. Price $20\nper acre.\nSee us in regard to any proposition.\nthat will interest you in regard to\nreal estate. GOOD CO.\nRooms 3 and 4, Terrell building.\n'Phone 357.\nThe expenditure i\neipal improveinens in\nif a few hundred thousand dollars for muni\n190 ought to be somewhat of a business\nbraeer.\ntin\nAll honor to the\npaving petitions.\nojo\npublic spirited\nThey are boost i\nolo\ncitizens who are\" peddling'\nrs of the proper sort.\nThe count ygame warden has and important notice\npaper to which hunters would better give heed.\nIhi\nSTATE OF OKLAHOMA,\nGrady County.\nIN THE DISTRICT COURT OF SAID\nCOUNTY\nGeorge Elliott, I'iahUiiTiT,\nvs.\nHomer Elliott, Defendant\nSaid defendant, Homer Elliott will\nlake notice that he ban been sued in\nthe above named court on the peti\ntion of faid plaintiff, Ceorge Eliott,\nivbo charges in said pet? i ion thnt the\npaid defendant abandoned and desert\ned this plaintiff nore than twelve\nmonths ago and has failed and refus\ned to ia any way support this plaint\niff for more, (ban two years and has\nteen guilty of cruel treatment to\nwards plaintiff and plaintiff prays a\ndecree of divorce dissolving tier mar\nriage to baid deiendant, must answer\nthe petition herein filed by said plaint\niff, before the thirtieth clay of March,\n1!0S, or said petition Mill be taken as\ntrue and a judgment for said plaint\niff for divorce will be reudered ac\ncordingly. J. II. CALLAII AM,\nClerk of the Disrict Court,\nGrady County, Oklahoma.\nIf. I j. GR1GSBY, Attorney for Plaint\niff. ADOLPI1US CLERK, Attorney for\nnonresident.\n(First published Jan. 17, JOOS.)\nSEAL\nSpecialties\nWe give each article we buy specla!\nattention, for we know quality\ncounts.\nWe have just received a shipment\nof the finest Dates that were ever\non the market, also a large box of\nMammoth Figs.\nEat Dates and Figs, better than\nmedicine for the system.\nIf yon want something fine in ma\nple syrup we have the pure article\nMonarch Brand. Try a can in your\nnext order. We also have just re\nceived a shipment of Ralston Buck\nWheat flour.\nTig nor Cash\nGhickasha\nAbstract\nCompany\nBGHDEO ABSTACTERS\nHave given Surety bond, con\nforming to the statutory re\nquirements under the Oklahoma\nlaws.\nT-oan romnanies reouire ab\nstracts made by Abstracters\nwho have given approved\nSURETY BOND.\nCHICKASHA ABSTRACT\nCOMPANY.\nPhone 300. Room 1, Johmon Eld'g\nPrompt Sale Correct\nCompounded, If You Bring Them Mere\nEvery package of medicine which leaves Our Prescription\nDepartment represents a correctly compounded prescription,\ninsuring you medicine of the utmost possible effectiveness if\nyou bring your doctor's prescription to us.\nCORRECT INGREDIENTS precisely the ingredients\nwhich your doctor specifies are put into your medicine when\nwe prepare the prescription. Nothing is \"substituted\" and\nnothing is put in which your doctor does not order,\nCORRECT QUANTITIES in all our prescription work\nthe quantity ot each individual ingredient is absolutely cor\nrect. Nothing is \"estimated\" nothing is \"guessed at\" ev\nerything must be AND IS exactly correct.\nCORRECT WORK every stage of the work of compound\ning is executed correctly, carefully and skillfully by an expert\nexperienced prescriptionist. In compounding prescriptions,\nwe offer you a service that in point of quality cannot be beat\nen anywhere.\nTin (Ml Drug Slere '2S\nAsh Your Grocer\nFor Pull Cream Flour\n'rm, Li- W\"\nif you want the best baking re\nsults. It has stood the test of\nmany an oven, and the bread,\nrolls, pies, cakes, etc., made\nfront it came out \"bright and\nsmiling\" when even a fair baker\nused it. Paste that name (or\nthis ad) in your pantry, plt'ase.\nChickasha Milling Company\nfl. P. BM1TH. Fraaldent\nW. W. HORN E. Vic Presidant,\nNo. SMT\nWlf. 1NMAN. Vie Praaldmt\nXD. V JOHNS. Cuhlai\nfi 1 fl 1\ntut llift!!ft il AWIiflpni\nInt OIIMLUIld tliUIU!IU!\nCHICKASUA, INDIAN TERRITORY,\nCapital 375,ooo.oo\nSurplus and Profits $45,ooo.oo\nYour Business Solicited\nDIKBCTORS\nB. T. SMITH WM. INMAN W. W. H0RN3 J